# Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

# Read the data
data=pd.read_csv("Data-week6.csv")

In [46]:
# Select the features (X) and target (Y)
X = data[['Month', 'Year', 'Temp']]
y = data['Day']

# Limit to the first 50 rows
X = X.iloc[:50, :]
y = y.iloc[:50]

# Split the data into train and test sets (25% test size)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=50, test_size=0.25)

# Define the DecisionTreeClassifier model
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()

# Fit the model
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Import necessary libraries 
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# Evaluate the model on training and test sets
print(accuracy_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=clf.predict(X_train)))
print(accuracy_score(y_true=y_test, y_pred=clf.predict(X_test)))

Interpretation based on accuracy :¶

When using the decision tree model, the accuracy of this model on the training set was 97.3%, which suggests that the model fits that training data very well. But as you can see in the table, the model’s accuracy was 0% on the test set. This could indicate that the model is over-fitted. Overfitting can be identified when there are usually complications in the model or where the number of training examples is narrow, hence the improper results found on the test set.¶

# Import libraries for plotting
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.tree import plot_tree

# Plot the decision tree and also include feature names for clarity
plt.figure(figsize=(100,50))
plot_tree(clf, filled=True, feature_names=['Month', 'Year', 'Temp'], class_names=True)
plt.show()

Interpretation based on the Decision Tree Structure :¶

The decision tree built uses temperature as the first attribute in splitting the data and generating a set of rules based on temperature intervals. The tree is based on temperature limits at various levels, such as very low temperature, that is, below -13.45°C, and other higher temperature levels. For example, if the temperature is below -13.45°C the predicted day is 10, and if the temperature is between -9.60 and -9.45°C the predicted day is 15. The tree does not appear to use the month or year features to any great extent, which may mean that temperature is the most important determinant of the day.¶
